obo:GO_0003674  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_3740  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Using an ELKS1/2 double knockout, this publication provides multiple lines of evidence that ELKS1 controls synaptic vesicle priming at excitatory synapses.\n\n-ELKS DKO leads to a reduction in spontaneous and action potential-evoked release at excitatory synapses (Figure 2).\n-ELKS DKO displays a reduction of sucrose-induced vesicle fusion, an established method for measuring vesicle priming. This effect can be rescued by reintroduction of ELKS1 (figure 7). In addition, there is a significant reduction in vesicle fusion during short action potential trains, which is in line with a defect in priming (figure 4).\n\n13/4/2017 Pim\n- Effect on priming may be synapse type related. In inhibitory synapses this effect seems absent although ELKS influences SV release via an indirect mechanism. (see ticket #333).. Experimental description: All experiments using mice were performed according to institutional guidelines at Harvard University. Conditional double knockout (cDKO) mice that remove the ELKS1α/2α proteins were generated by crossing conditional knockout mice for the Erc1 ([Liu et al., 2014] RRID:IMSR_JAX:015830) and Erc2 ([Kaeser et al., 2009] RRID:IMSR_JAX:015831) genes. ELKS1α/2α cDKO mice were maintained as double homozygote line." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-07" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3740" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

